## Learn: Graphing Power Functions

A power function is any function of the form `f(x) = ax^n`, where `a` and `n` are nonzero real numbers.

* `a` is the leading coefficient
* `n` is the degree
* A power function with positive integer `n` is called a monomial function

### Key Concept: End Behavior of a Monomial Function

* Even degree, positive leading coefficient:
  * as `x -> -infinity`, `f(x) -> infinity`
  * as `x -> infinity`, `f(x) -> infinity`
  * domain: all real numbers
  * range: `y >= 0`
* Odd degree, positive leading coefficient:
  * as `x -> -infinity`, `f(x) -> -infinity`
  * as `x -> infinity`, `f(x) -> infinity`
  * domain: all real numbers
  * range: all real numbers
* Even degree, negative leading coefficient:
  * as `x -> -infinity`, `f(x) -> -infinity`
  * as `x -> infinity`, `f(x) -> -infinity`
  * domain: all real numbers
  * range: `y <= 0`
* Odd degree, negative leading coefficient:
  * as `x -> -infinity`, `f(x) -> infinity`
  * as `x -> infinity`, `f(x) -> -infinity`
  * domain: all real numbers
  * range: all real numbers

### Key Concept: Zeros of Even- and Odd-Degree Monomial Functions

* Odd-degree functions always have at least one real zero
* Even-degree functions may have any number of real zeros or no real zeros at all

