## Example 4 — Evaluate and Graph a Polynomial Function

The density of the Sun can be modeled by:

`f(x) = 519x^4 - 1630x^3 + 1844x^2 - 889x + 155`

where `x` is the percent of the distance from the core to the surface, written as a decimal.

### Part A: Evaluate the function

Find the density at a radius `60%` of the way to the surface.

Substitute `x = 0.6`:

`f(0.6) = 519(0.6)^4 - 1630(0.6)^3 + 1844(0.6)^2 - 889(0.6) + 155`

`= 67.2624 - 352.08 + 663.84 - 533.4 + 155`

`= 0.6224`

So the density is `0.6224 g/cm^3`.

